english:
  title: Preface to the Comprehensive Collection of Native Korean Medicines for Healing and Life
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Medicine and healing remedies exist to cure both grave and minor ailments—this is one dimension of benevolent governance. In ancient times, Shenong caused Qibo to taste the grasses and barks, establishing the art of healing for disease. The Zhou Rituals speak of physicians who oversaw medical affairs and gathered medicines for healing work. Thereafter, skilled healers like Yu Fu, Bian Que, Yi He, and Yi Huan appeared throughout the records, though their writings were not transmitted to us. From the Tang dynasty onward, medical formulas multiplied with each generation, yet as formulas grew more numerous, the art itself became more scattered. For the great physicians of old used but a single substance to treat a single ailment, while later physicians mixed many substances, hoping fortune might grant them efficacy. Thus the renowned Tang physician Xu Yunzong was criticized with the apt metaphor: "In hunting without knowing where the hare hides, one casts wide nets across the whole field." Indeed, to combine many medicines for one disease is less precise than employing a single substance rightly chosen. Yet the difficulty lies not in the method, but in truly knowing the disease and applying the remedy with perfect understanding.

    Our Eastern realm, remote from the Middle Kingdom, suffers from the scarcity of medicines not native to our soil. Yet our people have discovered that a single grass often cures a single disease with remarkable efficacy. Long ago there existed the *Collection of Native Medicines*, admirably concise, though scholars lamented its brevity. Previously, the esteemed Kwon Jung-hwa, Minister of the Gate, commissioned one Seo Chan to supplement it with numerous formulas, creating the *Simple and Easy Methods*—a work not yet widely circulated.

    Humble reflection upon our sovereign lord: endowed with benevolence and sage wisdom, receiving the mandate to establish our realm, his vision to bestow blessings and save multitudes knows no bounds. Yet he grieves constantly that poor commoners, stricken by illness, lack means for healing. In deep compassion, the Left Prime Minister, the Count of Pyongyang, Zhao Jun, and the Right Prime Minister, the Count of Shangluo, Kim Sa-hyung, responding to his sacred heart, petitioned to establish throughout the realm the *Healing Life Institutes*, staffed with servants and supplied with native medicinal materials, to prepare remedies and distribute them widely for the people's benefit. The Central Council Chief Kim Hee-seon oversaw this great work. Medical academies were established in each province, instructors dispatched, remedies dispensed according to formula, that all might benefit eternally.

    Fearing gaps in the existing formulas, the sovereign specially commanded the Bureau of Pharmaceuticals to reexamine all methods and gather the tried experiences of our people, organizing them by category into this work, *The Comprehensive Collection of Native Korean Medicines for Healing and Life*, to which we have appended veterinary treatments for cattle and horses. When Kim Hee-seon became inspector of Kangwon, he gathered craftsmen to carve these texts upon wooden blocks, printing many copies for wide distribution. All these are substances easily obtained, all methods already proven. Mastering this alone, one need employ but a single remedy for a single disease—what need then for foreign substances difficult to procure?

    Moreover, the five regions each possess their own nature, and winds differ across a thousand li. In daily life, people's tastes in food—their preference for sour, salty, cold, and warm—vary by region. Thus the medicines suited to disease must also vary by locale; we need not slavishly follow the prescriptions of the Middle Kingdom. How much more so when foreign substances, having been sought but not obtained, arrive too late as the disease deepens, and though obtained at great cost, have grown old, spoiled, and worm-eaten, their vital essence already dispersed? Local medicines, whose essence remains intact, prove far superior. Thus treating disease with native remedies requires less effort yet yields faster results. What blessing does this collection bestow upon the people!

    The Classics teach: "The supreme physician heals the state itself." Now, when wise ruler and virtuous minister meet, when great fortune opens, their purpose is to rescue our people from suffering and establish our realm upon enduring stone. Laboring night and day with utmost dedication to governance, they scheme ever how to vitalize the people's life and strengthen the nation's pulse. In policies of love for the people and ways to enrich the realm, both root and branch are tended, all matters both great and small provided for. Even to the matter of medicine and healing, such devotion is lavished! How they nurture the people's vital essence, how they cultivate the nation's foundation—with such care and completeness. Truly, their healing of the state is great. Their benevolence covers this age; its blessings flow through ten thousand generations—can such things be easily measured?
  footnotes:
    - Shenong (神農), the legendary culture-hero and founder of agriculture in Chinese mythology.
    - The Zhou Rituals (周禮) is one of the foundational Confucian texts on governance.
    - Yu Fu (兪跗), Bian Que (扁鵲), Yi He (醫和), and Yi Huan (醫緩) were renowned physicians of ancient China.
    - Xu Yunzong (許胤宗) was a celebrated Tang dynasty physician known for his critical approach to medical practice.
    - The "five regions" refer to the five cardinal directions, each with its own climatic and cultural characteristics in traditional cosmology.
